<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/GE_Honda_Aero_Engines" title="GE Honda Aero Engines">GE Honda Aero Engines</a>(50%)</li>
</ul>
International
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Honda_Atlas" title="Honda Atlas">Honda Pakistan</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Honda_Canada_Inc." title="Honda Canada Inc.">Honda Canada Inc.</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Honda_Taiwan" title="Honda Taiwan">Honda Taiwan</a></li>

<tr>
<th scope="row" style="padding-right:0.5em;">Website</th>
<td style="line-height:1.35em;"><span class="url"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://world.honda.com/">world<wbr />.honda<wbr />.com</a></span></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Honda Motor Co., Ltd.</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji" lang="ja">本田技研工業株式会社</span><span class="t_nihongo_comma" style="display:none">,</span> <i>Honda Giken Kōgyō <a href="/wiki/Kabushiki_gaisha" title="Kabushiki gaisha">KK</a></i><sup class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><a href="/wiki/Help:Installing_Japanese_character_sets" title="Help:Installing Japanese character sets"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup>, <small>IPA:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Japanese" title="Help:IPA for Japanese">[hoɴda]</a></span><small class="nowrap metadata">&#160;(<a href="/wiki/File:Honda_giken_kougyou.ogg" title="File:Honda giken kougyou.ogg"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/13px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png" width="13" height="13" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/20px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/26px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="500" /></a> <a href="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e3/Honda_giken_kougyou.ogg" class="internal" title="Honda giken kougyou.ogg">listen</a>)</small>; <span class="nowrap"><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="/ˈ/ primary stress follows">ˈ</span><span title="'h' in 'hi'">h</span><span title="/ɒ/ short 'o' in 'body'">ɒ</span><span title="'n' in 'no'">n</span><span title="'d' in 'dye'">d</span><span title="/ə/ 'a' in 'about'">ə</span></span>/</a></span></span>)</span> is a Japanese <a href="/wiki/Public_company" title="Public company">public</a> <a href="/wiki/Multinational_corporation" title="Multinational corporation">multinational</a> <a href="/wiki/Conglomerate_(company)" title="Conglomerate (company)">conglomerate</a> corporation primarily known as a manufacturer of automobiles, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Aircraft_Company" title="Honda Aircraft Company">aircraft</a>, motorcycles, and power equipment.</p>
<p>Honda has been the world's largest motorcycle manufacturer since 1959,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> as well as the world's largest manufacturer of <a href="/wiki/Internal_combustion_engine" title="Internal combustion engine">internal combustion engines</a> measured by volume, producing more than 14 million internal combustion engines each year.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda_of_America_Manufacturing.2C_Inc..2C_Marysville.2C_Ohio_-_Press_room_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda_of_America_Manufacturing.2C_Inc..2C_Marysville.2C_Ohio_-_Press_room-4">[4]</a></sup> Honda became the second-largest Japanese automobile manufacturer in 2001.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> Honda was the eighth largest automobile manufacturer in the world behind <a href="/wiki/General_Motors" title="General Motors">General Motors</a>, <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_Group" title="Volkswagen Group">Volkswagen Group</a>, <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hyundai_Motor_Group" title="Hyundai Motor Group">Hyundai Motor Group</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nissan" title="Nissan">Nissan</a>, and <a href="/wiki/PSA_Peugeot_Citro%C3%ABn" class="mw-redirect" title="PSA Peugeot Citroën">PSA Peugeot Citroën</a> in 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup></p>
<p>Honda was the first Japanese automobile manufacturer to release a dedicated luxury brand, <a href="/wiki/Acura" title="Acura">Acura</a>, in 1986. Aside from their core automobile and motorcycle businesses, Honda also manufactures garden equipment, marine engines, personal watercraft and power generators, and other products. Since 1986, Honda has been involved with artificial intelligence/robotics research and released their <a href="/wiki/ASIMO" title="ASIMO">ASIMO</a> robot in 2000. They have also ventured into aerospace with the establishment of <a href="/wiki/GE_Honda_Aero_Engines" title="GE Honda Aero Engines">GE Honda Aero Engines</a> in 2004 and the <a href="/wiki/Honda_HA-420_HondaJet" title="Honda HA-420 HondaJet">Honda HA-420 HondaJet</a>, which began production in 2012. Honda has three joint-ventures in China (<a href="/wiki/Honda_Automobile_(China)_Company" title="Honda Automobile (China) Company">Honda China</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dongfeng_Honda" title="Dongfeng Honda">Dongfeng Honda</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Guangqi_Honda" title="Guangqi Honda">Guangqi Honda</a>).</p>
<p>In 2013, Honda invested about 5.7% (US$6.8 billion) of its revenues in research and development.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> Also in 2013, Honda became the first Japanese automaker to be a net exporter from the United States, exporting 108,705 Honda and Acura models, while importing only 88,357.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup></p>
<p></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<p>Throughout his life, Honda's founder, <a href="/wiki/Soichiro_Honda" title="Soichiro Honda">Soichiro Honda</a> had an interest in automobiles. He worked as a mechanic at the Art Shokai garage, where he tuned cars and entered them in races. In 1937, with financing from his acquaintance Kato Shichirō, Honda founded <a href="/wiki/T%C5%8Dkai_region" title="Tōkai region">Tōkai</a> Seiki (Eastern Sea Precision Machine Company) to make <a href="/wiki/Piston_ring" title="Piston ring">piston rings</a> working out of the Art Shokai garage.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> After initial failures, Tōkai Seiki won a contract to supply piston rings to <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a>, but lost the contract due to the poor quality of their products.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> After attending engineering school without graduating, and visiting factories around Japan to better understand Toyota's quality control processes, by 1941 Honda was able to mass-produce piston rings acceptable to Toyota, using an automated process that could employ even unskilled wartime laborers.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:16–19</sup></p>
<p><a href="/w/index.php?title=T%C5%8Dkai_Seiki&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tōkai Seiki (page does not exist)">Tōkai Seiki</a> was placed under control of the <a href="/wiki/Ministry_of_Commerce_and_Industry" class="mw-redirect" title="Ministry of Commerce and Industry">Ministry of Commerce and Industry</a> (called the Ministry of Munitions after 1943) at the start of World War II, and Soichiro Honda was demoted from president to senior managing director after Toyota took a 40% stake in the company.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> Honda also aided the war effort by assisting other companies in automating the production of military aircraft propellers.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> The relationships Honda cultivated with personnel at Toyota, <a href="/wiki/Nakajima_Aircraft_Company" title="Nakajima Aircraft Company">Nakajima Aircraft Company</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japanese_Navy" title="Imperial Japanese Navy">Imperial Japanese Navy</a> would be instrumental in the postwar period.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> A US <a href="/wiki/B-29" class="mw-redirect" title="B-29">B-29</a> bomber attack destroyed Tōkai Seiki's Yamashita plant in 1944, and the Itawa plant collapsed in the 13 January <a href="/wiki/1945_Mikawa_earthquake" title="1945 Mikawa earthquake">1945 Mikawa earthquake</a>, and Soichiro Honda sold the salvageable remains of the company to Toyota after the war for ¥450,000, and used the proceeds to found the Honda Technical Research Institute in October 1946.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Falloon2005_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Falloon2005-12">[12]</a></sup></p>
<p>With a staff of 12 men working in a 16&#160;m<sup>2</sup> (170&#160;sq&#160;ft) shack, they built and sold improvised <a href="/wiki/Motorized_bicycles" class="mw-redirect" title="Motorized bicycles">motorized bicycles</a>, using a supply of 500 <a href="/wiki/Two-stroke" class="mw-redirect" title="Two-stroke">two-stroke</a> <i>50&#160;cc</i> <a href="/wiki/Tohatsu" title="Tohatsu">Tohatsu</a> <a href="/wiki/War_surplus" class="mw-redirect" title="War surplus">war surplus</a> radio <a href="/wiki/Engine-generator" title="Engine-generator">generator engines</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:19</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Sakiya1982_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sakiya1982-13">[13]</a></sup> When the engines ran out, Honda began building their own copy of the Tohatsu engine, and supplying these to customers to attach to their bicycles.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Sakiya1982_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sakiya1982-13">[13]</a></sup> This was the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Honda_A-Type&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Honda A-Type (page does not exist)">Honda A-Type</a>, nicknamed the Bata Bata for the sound the engine made.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> In 1949, the Honda Technical Research Institute was liquidated for <span style="white-space: nowrap">¥</span>1,000,000, or about <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$</span>5,000 today; these funds were used to incorporate Honda Motor Co., Ltd.<sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:21</sup> At about the same time Honda hired engineer Kihachiro Kawashima, and <a href="/wiki/Takeo_Fujisawa" title="Takeo Fujisawa">Takeo Fujisawa</a> who provided indispensable business and marketing expertise to complement Soichiro Honda's technical bent.<sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:21</sup> The close partnership between Soichiro Honda and Fujisawa lasted until they stepped down together in October 1973.<sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:21</sup></p>
<p>The first complete motorcycle, with both the frame and engine made by Honda, was the 1949 <a href="/wiki/Honda_D-Type" title="Honda D-Type">D-Type</a>, the first Honda to go by the name Dream.<sup id="cite_ref-Falloon2005_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Falloon2005-12">[12]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> Honda Motor Company grew in a short time to become the world's largest manufacturer of motorcycles by 1964.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2015)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>The first production automobile from Honda was the <a href="/wiki/Honda_T360" title="Honda T360">T360</a> mini pick-up truck, which went on sale in August 1963.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> Powered by a small 356-cc straight-4 gasoline engine, it was classified under the cheaper <a href="/wiki/Kei_car" title="Kei car">Kei car</a> tax bracket.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> The first production car from Honda was the <a href="/wiki/Honda_S500" title="Honda S500">S500</a> sports car, which followed the T360 into production in October 1963. Its chain-driven rear wheels pointed to Honda's motorcycle origins.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup></p>
<p>Over the next few decades, Honda worked to expand its product line and expanded operations and exports to numerous countries around the world. In 1986, Honda introduced the successful <a href="/wiki/Acura" title="Acura">Acura</a> brand to the American market in an attempt to gain ground in the <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">luxury vehicle</a> market. The year 1991 saw the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Honda_NSX" title="Honda NSX">Honda NSX</a> supercar, the first all-aluminum monocoque vehicle that incorporated a mid-engine V6 with variable-valve timing.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup></p>
<p>CEO <a href="/wiki/Tadashi_Kume" title="Tadashi Kume">Tadashi Kume</a> was succeeded by <a href="/wiki/Nobuhiko_Kawamoto" title="Nobuhiko Kawamoto">Nobuhiko Kawamoto</a> in 1990. Kawamoto was selected over <a href="/wiki/Shoichiro_Irimajiri" title="Shoichiro Irimajiri">Shoichiro Irimajiri</a>, who oversaw the successful establishment of Honda of America Manufacturing, Inc. in <a href="/wiki/Marysville,_Ohio" title="Marysville, Ohio">Marysville, Ohio</a>. Both Kawamoto and Irimajiri shared a friendly rivalry within Honda, and Irimajiri would resign in 1992 due to health issues.</p>
<p>Following the death of <a href="/wiki/Soichiro_Honda" title="Soichiro Honda">Soichiro Honda</a> and the departure of Irimajiri, Honda found itself quickly being outpaced in product development by other Japanese automakers and was caught off-guard by the truck and <a href="/wiki/Sport_utility_vehicle" title="Sport utility vehicle">sport utility vehicle</a> boom of the 1990s, all which took a toll on the profitability of the company. Japanese media reported in 1992 and 1993 that Honda was at serious risk of an unwanted and hostile takeover by <a href="/wiki/Mitsubishi_Motors" title="Mitsubishi Motors">Mitsubishi Motors</a>, who at the time was a larger automaker by volume and flush with profits from their successful <a href="/wiki/Mitsubishi_Pajero" title="Mitsubishi Pajero">Pajero</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mitsubishi_Diamante" title="Mitsubishi Diamante">Diamante</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Economist_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Economist-20">[20]</a></sup></p>
<p>Kawamoto acted quickly to change Honda's corporate culture, rushing through market-driven product development that resulted in recreational vehicles such as the first generation <a href="/wiki/Honda_Odyssey_(international)#First_generation_.28RA1-RA5_chassis.29_.281994.E2.80.931999.29" title="Honda Odyssey (international)">Odyssey</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Honda_CR-V" title="Honda CR-V">CR-V</a>, and a refocusing away from some of the numerous sedans and coupes that were popular with Honda's engineers but not with the buying public. The most shocking change to Honda came when Kawamoto ended Honda's successful participation in Formula One after the 1992 season, citing costs in light of the takeover threat from Mitsubishi as well as the desire to create a more environmentally-friendly company image.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup></p>
<p>Later, 1995 gave rise to the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Aircraft_Company" title="Honda Aircraft Company">Honda Aircraft Company</a> with the goal of producing jet aircraft under Honda's name.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup></p>
<p>On 23 February 2015, Honda announced that CEO and President <a href="/wiki/Takanobu_Ito" title="Takanobu Ito">Takanobu Ito</a> would step down and be replaced by Takahiro Hachigo by June; additional retirements by senior managers and directors were expected.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_profile_and_divisions">Corporate profile and divisions</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_aoyama.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Honda_aoyama.JPG/170px-Honda_aoyama.JPG" width="170" height="225" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Honda_aoyama.JPG/255px-Honda_aoyama.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Honda_aoyama.JPG/340px-Honda_aoyama.JPG 2x" data-file-width="863" data-file-height="1142" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_aoyama.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Minato,_Tokyo" title="Minato, Tokyo">Honda headquarters</a> building in <a href="/wiki/Minato,_Tokyo" title="Minato, Tokyo">Minato, Tokyo</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Honda</b> is headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Minato,_Tokyo" title="Minato, Tokyo">Minato</a>, Tokyo, Japan. Their shares trade on the <a href="/wiki/Tokyo_Stock_Exchange" title="Tokyo Stock Exchange">Tokyo Stock Exchange</a> and the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Stock_Exchange" title="New York Stock Exchange">New York Stock Exchange</a>, as well as exchanges in Osaka, Nagoya, Sapporo, Kyoto, <a href="/wiki/Fukuoka,_Fukuoka" class="mw-redirect" title="Fukuoka, Fukuoka">Fukuoka</a>, London, Paris and Switzerland.</p>
<p>The company has assembly plants around the globe. These plants are located in China, the United States, Pakistan, Canada, England, Japan, Belgium, Brazil, México, New Zealand, Malaysia, Indonesia, India, Philippines, Thailand, Vietnam, Turkey, Taiwan, Perú and Argentina. As of July 2010, 89 percent of Honda and Acura vehicles sold in the United States were built in North American plants, up from 82.2 percent a year earlier. This shields profits from the yen's advance to a 15-year high against the dollar.<sup id="cite_ref-bloomberg.com_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bloomberg.com-24">[24]</a></sup></p>

<p><a href="/wiki/American_Honda_Motor_Company" title="American Honda Motor Company">American Honda Motor Company</a> is based in Torrance, California. <a href="/wiki/Honda_Racing_Corporation" title="Honda Racing Corporation">Honda Racing Corporation</a> (HRC) is Honda's motorcycle racing division. <a href="/wiki/Honda_Canada_Inc." title="Honda Canada Inc.">Honda Canada Inc.</a> is headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Markham,_Ontario" title="Markham, Ontario">Markham, Ontario</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> their manufacturing division, <a href="/wiki/Honda_of_Canada_Manufacturing" title="Honda of Canada Manufacturing">Honda of Canada Manufacturing</a>, is based in <a href="/wiki/Alliston,_Ontario" class="mw-redirect" title="Alliston, Ontario">Alliston, Ontario</a>. Honda has also created joint ventures around the world, such as <a href="/wiki/Honda_Siel_Cars_India" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Siel Cars India">Honda Siel Cars</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hero_Honda" class="mw-redirect" title="Hero Honda">Hero Honda Motorcycles</a> in India,<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Guangzhou_Automobile_Industry_Group" title="Guangzhou Automobile Industry Group">Guangzhou Honda</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dongfeng_Honda" title="Dongfeng Honda">Dongfeng Honda</a> in China, Boon Siew Honda in Malaysia and <a href="/wiki/Honda_Atlas" title="Honda Atlas">Honda Atlas</a> in Pakistan.</p>
<p>Following the Japanese earthquake and tsunami in March 2011 Honda announced plans to halve production at its UK plants.<sup id="cite_ref-Guardian6April2011_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Guardian6April2011-28">[28]</a></sup> The decision was made to put staff at the Swindon plant on a 2-day week until the end of May as the manufacturer struggled to source supplies from Japan. It's thought around 22,500 cars were produced during this period.</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Products">Products</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Automobiles">Automobiles</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">For a list of automobiles, see <a href="/wiki/List_of_Honda_automobiles" title="List of Honda automobiles">List of Honda automobiles</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_(2016-01-07)_01.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_%282016-01-07%29_01.jpg/220px-2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_%282016-01-07%29_01.jpg" width="220" height="89" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_%282016-01-07%29_01.jpg/330px-2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_%282016-01-07%29_01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_%282016-01-07%29_01.jpg/440px-2014_Honda_Accord_2.4_i-VTEC_sedan_%282016-01-07%29_01.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3813" data-file-height="1550" /></a>

<div class="thumb tright">

<div class="thumbcaption">

<a href="/wiki/Honda_CR-Z" title="Honda CR-Z">Honda CR-Z</a>, the first sports coupe hybrid to come with a six-speed manual transmission</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Honda's global lineup consists of the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit" title="Honda Fit">Fit</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic" title="Honda Civic">Civic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord" title="Honda Accord">Accord</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Insight" title="Honda Insight">Insight</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_CR-V" title="Honda CR-V">CR-V</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_CR-Z" title="Honda CR-Z">CR-Z</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Legend" title="Honda Legend">Legend</a> and two versions of the Odyssey, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Odyssey_(North_America)" title="Honda Odyssey (North America)">one for North America</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Honda_Odyssey_(international)" title="Honda Odyssey (international)">a smaller vehicle</a> sold internationally. An early proponent of developing vehicles to cater to different needs and markets worldwide, Honda's lineup varies by country and may have vehicles exclusive to that region. A few examples are the latest <a href="/wiki/Honda_Odyssey_(North_America)" title="Honda Odyssey (North America)">Honda Odyssey</a> <a href="/wiki/Minivan" title="Minivan">minivan</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Ridgeline" title="Honda Ridgeline">Ridgeline</a>, Honda's first light-duty uni-body <a href="/wiki/Pickup_truck" title="Pickup truck">pickup truck</a>. Both were designed and engineered primarily in North America and are produced there. Other example of exclusive models includes the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_(eighth_generation)#Europe" title="Honda Civic (eighth generation)">Honda Civic five-door hatchback</a> sold in Europe.</p>
<p>Honda's automotive manufacturing ambitions can be traced back to 1963, with the <a href="/wiki/Honda_T360" title="Honda T360">Honda T360</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Kei_car" title="Kei car">kei car</a> truck built for the Japanese market.<sup id="cite_ref-tjra_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tjra-29">[29]</a></sup> This was followed by the two-door <a href="/wiki/Roadster_(automobile)" title="Roadster (automobile)">roadster</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_S500" title="Honda S500">Honda S500</a> also introduced in 1963. In 1965, Honda built a two-door commercial delivery van, called the <a href="/wiki/Honda_L700" title="Honda L700">Honda L700</a>. Honda's first four-door sedan was not the Accord, but the air-cooled, four-cylinder, gasoline-powered <a href="/wiki/Honda_1300" title="Honda 1300">Honda 1300</a> in 1969. The Civic was a hatchback that gained wide popularity internationally, but it wasn't the first two-door hatchback built. That was the <a href="/wiki/Honda_N360" title="Honda N360">Honda N360</a>, another <i>Kei car</i> that was adapted for international sale as the N600. The Civic, which appeared in 1972 and replaced the N600 also had a smaller sibling that replaced the air-cooled N360, called the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Life" title="Honda Life">Honda Life</a> that was water-cooled.</p>
<p>The Honda Life represented Honda's efforts in competing in the <i>kei</i> car segment, offering sedan, delivery van and small pick-up platforms on a shared chassis. The <a href="/wiki/Honda_Life#Life_Step_Van" title="Honda Life">Life StepVan</a> had a novel approach that, while not initially a commercial success, appears to be an influence in vehicles with the front passengers sitting behind the engine, a large cargo area with a flat roof and a liftgate installed in back, and utilizing a transversely installed engine with a front-wheel-drive powertrain.</p>
<p>As Honda entered into automobile manufacturing in the late 1960s, where Japanese manufacturers such as Toyota and Nissan had been making cars since before WWII, it appears that Honda instilled a sense of doing things a little differently than its Japanese competitors. Its mainstay products, like the Accord and Civic (with the exception of its USA-market 1993–97 Passport which was part of a vehicle exchange program with Isuzu (part of the Subaru-Isuzu joint venture)), have always employed <a href="/wiki/Front-wheel-drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Front-wheel-drive">front-wheel-drive</a> powertrain implementation, which is currently a long held Honda tradition. Honda also installed new technologies into their products, first as optional equipment, then later standard, like anti lock brakes, speed sensitive power steering, and multi-port fuel injection in the early 1980s. This desire to be the first to try new approaches is evident with the creation of the first Japanese luxury chain <a href="/wiki/Acura" title="Acura">Acura</a>, and was also evident with the all aluminum, mid-engined sports car, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_NSX" title="Honda NSX">Honda NSX</a>, which also introduced <a href="/wiki/Variable_valve_timing" title="Variable valve timing">variable valve timing</a> technology, Honda calls <a href="/wiki/VTEC" title="VTEC">VTEC</a>.</p>
<p>The Civic is a line of <a href="/wiki/Compact_car" title="Compact car">compact cars</a> developed and manufactured by Honda. In North America, the Civic is the second-longest continuously running nameplate from a Japanese manufacturer; only its perennial rival, the <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Corolla" title="Toyota Corolla">Toyota Corolla</a>, introduced in 1968, has been in production longer.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> The Civic, along with the Accord and <a href="/wiki/Honda_Prelude" title="Honda Prelude">Prelude</a>, comprised Honda's vehicles sold in North America until the 1990s, when the model lineup was expanded. Having gone through several generational changes, the Civic has become larger and more <a href="/wiki/Upmarket" class="mw-redirect" title="Upmarket">upmarket</a>, and it currently slots between the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit" title="Honda Fit">Fit</a> and Accord.</p>
<p>Honda produces <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_Hybrid" title="Honda Civic Hybrid">Civic hybrid</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">hybrid electric vehicle</a> that competes with the <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Prius" title="Toyota Prius">Toyota Prius</a>, and also produces the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Insight" title="Honda Insight">Insight</a> and <a href="/wiki/Honda_CR-Z" title="Honda CR-Z">CR-Z</a>.</p>
<p>In 2008, Honda increased global production to meet demand for <a href="/wiki/Small_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Small car">small cars</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_vehicle" title="Hybrid vehicle">hybrids</a> in the U.S. and emerging markets. The company shuffled U.S. production to keep factories busy and boost car output, while building fewer <a href="/wiki/Minivan" title="Minivan">minivans</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sport_utility_vehicle" title="Sport utility vehicle">sport utility vehicles</a> as <a href="/wiki/Light-truck" class="mw-redirect" title="Light-truck">light truck</a> sales fell.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup></p>
<p>Its first entrance into the pickup segment, the light duty Ridgeline, won Truck of the Year from <i><a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend" title="Motor Trend">Motor Trend</a></i> magazine in 2006. Also in 2006, the redesigned Civic won <a href="/wiki/Motor_Trend_Car_of_the_Year" title="Motor Trend Car of the Year">Car of the Year</a> from the magazine, giving Honda a rare double win of Motor Trend honors. Honda's 9th generation Civic also won the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.pakwheels.com/awards/2014">Car of the Year</a> award based on a public survey held by <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.pakwheels.com/">PakWheels</a></p>
<p>It is reported that Honda plans to increase hybrid sales in Japan to more than 20% of its total sales in fiscal year 2011, from 14.8% in previous year.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup></p>
<p>Five of <a href="/wiki/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency" title="United States Environmental Protection Agency">United States Environmental Protection Agency</a>'s top ten most fuel-efficient cars from 1984 to 2010 comes from Honda, more than any other automakers. The five models are: 2000–2006 Honda Insight (53&#160;mpg<sub>‑US</sub> or 4.4&#160;L/100&#160;km or 64&#160;mpg<sub>‑imp</sub> combined), 1986–1987 Honda Civic Coupe HF (46&#160;mpg<sub>‑US</sub> or 5.1&#160;L/100&#160;km or 55&#160;mpg<sub>‑imp</sub> combined), 1994–1995 Honda Civic hatchback VX (43&#160;mpg<sub>‑US</sub> or 5.5&#160;L/100&#160;km or 52&#160;mpg<sub>‑imp</sub> combined), 2006– Honda Civic Hybrid (42&#160;mpg<sub>‑US</sub> or 5.6&#160;L/100&#160;km or 50&#160;mpg<sub>‑imp</sub> combined), and 2010– Honda Insight (41&#160;mpg<sub>‑US</sub> or 5.7&#160;L/100&#160;km or 49&#160;mpg<sub>‑imp</sub> combined).<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/American_Council_for_an_Energy-Efficient_Economy" title="American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy">ACEEE</a> has also rated the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_GX" title="Honda Civic GX">Civic GX</a> as the greenest car in America for seven consecutive years.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorcycles">Motorcycles</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">For a list of motorcycle products, see <a href="/wiki/List_of_Honda_motorcycles" title="List of Honda motorcycles">List of Honda motorcycles</a>.</div>
<p>Honda is the largest motorcycle manufacturer in Japan and has been since it started production in 1955.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup> At its peak in 1982, Honda manufactured almost three million motorcycles annually. By 2006 this figure had reduced to around 550,000 but was still higher than its three domestic competitors.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexander2008_10-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexander2008-10">[10]</a></sup></p>
<p>During the 1960s, when it was a small manufacturer, Honda broke out of the Japanese motorcycle market and began exporting to the U.S. Working with the advertising agency <a href="/wiki/Grey_Advertising" class="mw-redirect" title="Grey Advertising">Grey Advertising</a>, Honda created an innovative marketing campaign, using the slogan "<a href="/wiki/You_meet_the_nicest_people_on_a_Honda" class="mw-redirect" title="You meet the nicest people on a Honda">You meet the nicest people on a Honda</a>." In contrast to the prevailing negative stereotypes of motorcyclists in America as tough, antisocial rebels, this campaign suggested that Honda motorcycles were made for the everyman. The campaign was hugely successful; the ads ran for three years, and by the end of 1963 alone, Honda had sold 90,000 motorcycles.<sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:{{{1}}}</sup></p>
<p>Taking Honda's story as an archetype of the smaller manufacturer entering a new market already occupied by highly dominant competitors, the story of their market entry, and their subsequent huge success in the U.S. and around the world, has been the subject of some academic controversy. Competing explanations have been advanced to explain Honda's strategy and the reasons for their success.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup></p>
<p>The first of these explanations was put forward when, in 1975, <a href="/wiki/Boston_Consulting_Group" title="Boston Consulting Group">Boston Consulting Group</a> (BCG) was commissioned by the UK government to write a report explaining why and how the British motorcycle industry had been out-competed by its Japanese competitors. The report concluded that the Japanese firms, including Honda, had sought a very high scale of production (they had made a large number of motorbikes) in order to benefit from <a href="/wiki/Economies_of_scale" title="Economies of scale">economies of scale</a> and <a href="/wiki/Learning_curve" title="Learning curve">learning curve</a> effects. It blamed the decline of the British motorcycle industry on the failure of British managers to invest enough in their businesses to profit from economies of scale and <a href="/wiki/Economies_of_scope" title="Economies of scope">scope</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Morrison_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Morrison-36">[36]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:2004supercub.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/2004supercub.jpg/220px-2004supercub.jpg" width="220" height="171" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/2004supercub.jpg/330px-2004supercub.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/2004supercub.jpg/440px-2004supercub.jpg 2x" data-file-width="585" data-file-height="454" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:2004supercub.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2004 <a href="/wiki/Honda_Super_Cub" title="Honda Super Cub">Honda Super Cub</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The second explanation was offered in 1984 by Richard Pascale, who had interviewed the Honda executives responsible for the firm's entry into the U.S. market. As opposed to the tightly focused strategy of low cost and high scale that BCG accredited to Honda, Pascale found that their entry into the U.S. market was a story of "miscalculation, serendipity, and organizational learning" – in other words, Honda's success was due to the adaptability and hard work of its staff, rather than any long term strategy.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> For example, Honda's initial plan on entering the US was to compete in large motorcycles, around 300&#160;cc. Honda's motorcycles in this class suffered performance and reliability problems when ridden the relatively long distances of the US highways.<sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:41–43</sup> When the team found that the scooters they were using to get themselves around their U.S. base of <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco" title="San Francisco">San Francisco</a> attracted positive interest from consumers that they fell back on selling the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Super_Cub" title="Honda Super Cub">Super Cub</a> instead.<sup id="cite_ref-Frank2003_11-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Frank2003-11">[11]</a></sup><sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:41–43</sup></p>
<p>The most recent school of thought on Honda's strategy was put forward by <a href="/wiki/Gary_Hamel" title="Gary Hamel">Gary Hamel</a> and <a href="/wiki/C._K._Prahalad" title="C. K. Prahalad">C. K. Prahalad</a> in 1989. Creating the concept of <a href="/wiki/Core_competency" title="Core competency">core competencies</a> with Honda as an example, they argued that Honda's success was due to its focus on leadership in the technology of internal combustion engines.<sup id="cite_ref-HamelPrahalad1994_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HamelPrahalad1994-38">[38]</a></sup> For example, the high power-to-weight ratio engines Honda produced for its racing bikes provided technology and expertise which was transferable into mopeds. Honda's entry into the U.S. motorcycle market during the 1960s is used as a <a href="/wiki/Case_study" title="Case study">case study</a> for teaching introductory strategy at <a href="/wiki/Business_school" title="Business school">business schools</a> worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-ClarkeLamoreaux2009_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ClarkeLamoreaux2009-39">[39]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Power_equipment">Power equipment</span></h3>
<p>Production started in 1953 with H-type engine (prior to motorcycle).<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup><br />
Honda power equipment reached record sales in 2007 with 6.4&#160;million units.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> By 2010 <small>(<a href="/wiki/Fiscal_year" title="Fiscal year">Fiscal year</a> ended 31 March)</small> this figure had decreased to 4,7&#160;million units.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> Cumulative production of power products has exceeded 85 million units (as of September 2008).<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup></p>
