<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Engines">Engines</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Hondaoutboard.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/53/Hondaoutboard.jpg/220px-Hondaoutboard.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/53/Hondaoutboard.jpg/330px-Hondaoutboard.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/53/Hondaoutboard.jpg/440px-Hondaoutboard.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Hondaoutboard.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Honda <a href="/wiki/Outboard_motor" title="Outboard motor">Outboard motor</a> on a <a href="/wiki/Pontoon_boat" class="mw-redirect" title="Pontoon boat">pontoon boat</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Honda engines powered the entire 33-car starting field of the <a href="/wiki/2010_Indianapolis_500" title="2010 Indianapolis 500">2010 Indianapolis 500</a><sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> and for the fifth consecutive race, there were no engine-related retirements during the running of the Memorial Day Classic.<sup id="cite_ref-INDY1_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-INDY1-45">[45]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the 1980s Honda developed the <a href="/wiki/GY6_engine" title="GY6 engine">GY6 engine</a> for use in motor scooters. Although no longer manufactured by Honda it is still commonly used in many Chinese, Korean and Taiwanese light vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-gy6_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gy6-46">[46]</a></sup></p>
<p>Honda, despite being known as an engine company, has never built a <a href="/wiki/V8_engine" title="V8 engine">V8</a> for passenger vehicles. In the late 1990s, the company resisted considerable pressure from its American dealers for a V8 engine (which would have seen use in top-of-the-line Honda SUVs and <a href="/wiki/Acura" title="Acura">Acuras</a>), with American Honda reportedly sending one dealer a shipment of <a href="/wiki/V8_(beverage)" title="V8 (beverage)">V8 beverages</a> to silence them.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup> Honda considered starting V8 production in the mid-2000s for larger Acura sedans, a new version of the high end NSX sports car (which previously used DOHC V6 engines with VTEC to achieve its high power output) and possible future ventures into the American full-size truck and SUV segment for both the Acura and Honda brands, but this was cancelled in late 2008, with Honda citing environmental and worldwide economic conditions as reasons for the termination of this project.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Robots">Robots</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:HONDA_ASIMO.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/HONDA_ASIMO.jpg/170px-HONDA_ASIMO.jpg" width="170" height="227" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/HONDA_ASIMO.jpg/255px-HONDA_ASIMO.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/HONDA_ASIMO.jpg/340px-HONDA_ASIMO.jpg 2x" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="1280" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:HONDA_ASIMO.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/ASIMO" title="ASIMO">ASIMO</a> at <a href="/wiki/Expo_2005" title="Expo 2005">Expo 2005</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/ASIMO" title="ASIMO">ASIMO</a> is the part of Honda's <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://world.honda.com/ASIMO/history/history.html">Research &amp; Development robotics program</a>. It is the eleventh in a line of successive builds starting in 1986 with <a href="/wiki/Honda_E0" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda E0">Honda E0</a> moving through the ensuing <a href="/wiki/Honda_E_series" title="Honda E series">Honda E series</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Honda_P_series" title="Honda P series">Honda P series</a>. Weighing 54 kilograms and standing 130 centimeters tall, ASIMO resembles a small <a href="/wiki/Astronaut" title="Astronaut">astronaut</a> wearing a backpack, and can walk on <a href="/wiki/Biped" class="mw-redirect" title="Biped">two feet</a> in a manner resembling human <a href="/wiki/Walking" title="Walking">locomotion</a>, at up to 6&#160;km/h (3.7&#160;mph). ASIMO is the world's only humanoid robot able to ascend and descend stairs independently.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> However, human motions such as climbing stairs are difficult to mimic with a machine, which ASIMO has demonstrated by taking two plunges off a staircase.</p>
<p>Honda's robot <a href="/wiki/ASIMO" title="ASIMO">ASIMO</a> (see below) as an R&amp;D project brings together expertise to create a robot that walks, dances and navigates steps. 2010 marks the year Honda has developed a machine capable of reading a user's brainwaves to move <a href="/wiki/ASIMO" title="ASIMO">ASIMO</a>. The system uses a helmet covered with electroencephalography and near-infrared spectroscopy sensors that monitor electrical brainwaves and cerebral blood flow—signals that alter slightly during the human thought process. The user thinks of one of a limited number of gestures it wants from the robot, which has been fitted with a Brain Machine Interface.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Aircraft">Aircraft</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Honda_HA-420_HondaJet" title="Honda HA-420 HondaJet">Honda HA-420 HondaJet</a></div>
<p>Honda has also pioneered new technology in its <a href="/wiki/Honda_HA-420_HondaJet" title="Honda HA-420 HondaJet">HA-420 HondaJet</a>, manufactured by its subsidiary <a href="/wiki/Honda_Aircraft_Company" title="Honda Aircraft Company">Honda Aircraft Company</a>, which allows new levels of reduced drag, increased aerodynamics and fuel efficiency thus reducing operating costs.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (December 2009)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Mountain_bikes">Mountain bikes</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Honda_RN-01_G-cross" title="Honda RN-01 G-cross">Honda RN-01 G-cross</a></div>
<p>Honda has also built a <a href="/wiki/Downhill_mountain_biking" title="Downhill mountain biking">downhill racing bicycle</a> known as the Honda RN-01. It is not available for sale to the public. The bike has a gearbox, which replaces the standard <a href="/wiki/Derailleur_gears" title="Derailleur gears">derailleur</a> found on most bikes.</p>
<p>Honda has hired several people to pilot the bike, among them <a href="/wiki/Greg_Minnaar" title="Greg Minnaar">Greg Minnaar</a>. The team is known as Team G Cross Honda.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Former_products">Former products</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="ATV">ATV</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Honda_Rincon" title="Honda Rincon">Honda Rincon</a></div>
<p>Honda also builds <a href="/wiki/All-terrain_vehicles" class="mw-redirect" title="All-terrain vehicles">all-terrain vehicles</a> (ATV). 450r 400ex 300ex 250r</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Solar_cells">Solar cells</span></h3>
<p>Honda's solar cell subsidiary company Honda Soltec (Headquarters: Kikuchi-gun, Kumamoto; President and CEO: Akio Kazusa) started sales throughout Japan of <a href="/wiki/Thin-film_solar_cells" class="mw-redirect" title="Thin-film solar cells">thin-film solar cells</a> for public and industrial use on 24 October 2008, after selling solar cells for residential use since October 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup> Honda announced in the end of October 2013 that Honda Soltec would cease the business operation except for support for existing customers in Spring 2014 and the subsidiary would be dissolved.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsports">Motorsports</span></h2>
<p>Honda has been active in motorsports, like Motorcycle Grand Prix, Superbike racing and others.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Automobile">Automobile</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Honda_in_Formula_One" title="Honda in Formula One">Honda in Formula One</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg/220px-Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg" width="220" height="106" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg/330px-Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg/440px-Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="619" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Rubens_Barrichello_2006_Brazil.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Rubens_Barrichello" title="Rubens Barrichello">Rubens Barrichello</a> driving for Honda</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Honda entered <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> as a constructor for the first time in the <a href="/wiki/1964_Formula_One_season" title="1964 Formula One season">1964 season</a> at the <a href="/wiki/1964_German_Grand_Prix" title="1964 German Grand Prix">German Grand Prix</a> with <a href="/wiki/Ronnie_Bucknum" title="Ronnie Bucknum">Ronnie Bucknum</a> at the wheel. <a href="/wiki/1965_Formula_One_season" title="1965 Formula One season">1965</a> saw the addition of <a href="/wiki/Richie_Ginther" title="Richie Ginther">Richie Ginther</a> to the team, who scored Honda's first point at the <a href="/wiki/1965_Belgian_Grand_Prix" title="1965 Belgian Grand Prix">Belgian Grand Prix</a>, and Honda's first win at the <a href="/wiki/1965_Mexican_Grand_Prix" title="1965 Mexican Grand Prix">Mexican Grand Prix</a>. <a href="/wiki/1967_Formula_One_season" title="1967 Formula One season">1967</a> saw their next win at the <a href="/wiki/1967_Italian_Grand_Prix" title="1967 Italian Grand Prix">Italian Grand Prix</a> with <a href="/wiki/John_Surtees" title="John Surtees">John Surtees</a> as their driver. In <a href="/wiki/1968_Formula_One_season" title="1968 Formula One season">1968</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jo_Schlesser" title="Jo Schlesser">Jo Schlesser</a> was killed in a Honda RA302 at the <a href="/wiki/1968_French_Grand_Prix" title="1968 French Grand Prix">French Grand Prix</a>. This racing tragedy, coupled with their commercial difficulties selling automobiles in the United States, prompted Honda to withdraw from all international motorsport that year.</p>
<p>After a learning year in 1965, Honda-powered <a href="/wiki/Brabham" title="Brabham">Brabhams</a> dominated the 1966 French <a href="/wiki/Formula_Two" title="Formula Two">Formula Two</a> championship in the hands of <a href="/wiki/Jack_Brabham" title="Jack Brabham">Jack Brabham</a> and <a href="/wiki/Denny_Hulme" title="Denny Hulme">Denny Hulme</a>. As there was no European Championship that season, this was the top F2 championship that year. In the early 1980s Honda returned to F2, supplying engines to <a href="/wiki/Ron_Tauranac" title="Ron Tauranac">Ron Tauranac</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Ralt" title="Ralt">Ralt</a> team. Tauranac had designed the Brabham cars for their earlier involvement. They were again extremely successful. In a related exercise, John Judd's <a href="/wiki/Judd_(engine)" title="Judd (engine)">Engine Developments</a> company produced a turbo "Brabham-Honda" engine for use in <a href="/wiki/Open_wheel_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Open wheel car">IndyCar</a> racing. It won only one race, in 1988 for <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Rahal" title="Bobby Rahal">Bobby Rahal</a> at Pocono.</p>
<p>Honda returned to Formula One in 1983, initially with another Formula Two partner, the <a href="/wiki/Spirit_(racing_team)" class="mw-redirect" title="Spirit (racing team)">Spirit</a> team, before switching abruptly to Williams in 1984. In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Honda powered cars won six consecutive <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> Constructors Championships. <a href="/wiki/WilliamsF1" class="mw-redirect" title="WilliamsF1">WilliamsF1</a> won the crown in <a href="/wiki/1986_Formula_One_season" title="1986 Formula One season">1986</a> and <a href="/wiki/1987_Formula_One_season" title="1987 Formula One season">1987</a>. Honda switched allegiance again in 1988. New partners Team <a href="/wiki/McLaren" title="McLaren">McLaren</a> won the title in <a href="/wiki/1988_Formula_One_season" title="1988 Formula One season">1988</a>, <a href="/wiki/1989_Formula_One_season" title="1989 Formula One season">1989</a>, <a href="/wiki/1990_Formula_One_season" title="1990 Formula One season">1990</a> and <a href="/wiki/1991_Formula_One_season" title="1991 Formula One season">1991</a>. Honda withdrew from Formula One at the end of 1992, although the related <a href="/wiki/Mugen-Honda" class="mw-redirect" title="Mugen-Honda">Mugen-Honda</a> company maintained a presence up to the end of 1999, winning four races with <a href="/wiki/Equipe_Ligier" title="Equipe Ligier">Ligier</a> and <a href="/wiki/Jordan_Grand_Prix" title="Jordan Grand Prix">Jordan Grand Prix</a>.</p>
<p>Honda debuted in the <a href="/wiki/Champ_Car" title="Champ Car">CART IndyCar World Series</a> as a works supplier in 1994. The engines were far from competitive at first, but after development, the company powered six consecutive drivers championships. In 2003, Honda transferred its effort to the rival <a href="/wiki/Indy_Racing_League" class="mw-redirect" title="Indy Racing League">IRL</a> <a href="/wiki/IndyCar_Series" title="IndyCar Series">IndyCar Series</a> with <a href="/wiki/Ilmor" title="Ilmor">Ilmor</a> as joint development until 2006. In 2004, Honda-powered cars overwhelmingly dominated the IndyCar Series, winning 14 of 16 IndyCar races, including the <a href="/wiki/Indianapolis_500" title="Indianapolis 500">Indianapolis 500</a>, and claimed the IndyCar Series Manufacturers' Championship, Drivers' Championship and Rookie of the Year titles. From 2006 to 2011, Honda was the lone engine supplier for the IndyCar Series, including the Indianapolis 500. In the <a href="/wiki/2006_Indianapolis_500" title="2006 Indianapolis 500">2006 Indianapolis 500</a>, for the first time in Indianapolis 500 history, the race was run without a single engine problem.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup> Since 2012, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Performance_Development" title="Honda Performance Development">HPD</a> has constructed turbocharged V-6 engines for its IndyCar effort.</p>
<p>During 1998, Honda considered returning to Formula One with their own team. The project was aborted after the death of its technical director, <a href="/wiki/Harvey_Postlethwaite" title="Harvey Postlethwaite">Harvey Postlethwaite</a>. Honda instead came back as an official engine supplier to <a href="/wiki/British_American_Racing" title="British American Racing">British American Racing</a> (BAR) and Jordan Grand Prix. Honda bought a stake in the BAR team in 2004 before buying the team outright at the end of 2005, becoming a constructor for the first time since the 1960s. Honda won the <a href="/wiki/2006_Hungarian_Grand_Prix" title="2006 Hungarian Grand Prix">2006 Hungarian Grand Prix</a> with driver <a href="/wiki/Jenson_Button" title="Jenson Button">Jenson Button</a>.</p>
<p>It was announced on 5 December 2008, that Honda would be exiting Formula One with immediate effect due to the 2008 global economic crisis.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup> The team was sold to former team principal <a href="/wiki/Ross_Brawn" title="Ross Brawn">Ross Brawn</a>, renamed <a href="/wiki/Brawn_GP" title="Brawn GP">Brawn GP</a> and subsequently <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_Formula_One" title="Mercedes-Benz in Formula One">Mercedes</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup></p>
<p>Honda became an official works team in the <a href="/wiki/British_Touring_Car_Championship" title="British Touring Car Championship">British Touring Car Championship</a> in 2010.</p>
<p>Honda made an official announcement on 16 May 2013 that it will re-enter Formula One racing in 2015 as an engine supplier to the <a href="/wiki/McLaren" title="McLaren">McLaren</a> team.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorcycles_2">Motorcycles</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Honda_Racing_Corporation" title="Honda Racing Corporation">Honda Racing Corporation</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg/220px-Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg/330px-Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg/440px-Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg 2x" data-file-width="685" data-file-height="514" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Dani_Pedrosa_2010_Assen.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Honda_RC212V" title="Honda RC212V">Honda RC212V</a> raced by <a href="/wiki/Dani_Pedrosa" title="Dani Pedrosa">Dani Pedrosa</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Honda_Racing_Corporation" title="Honda Racing Corporation">Honda Racing Corporation</a> (HRC) was formed in 1982. The company combines participation in motorcycle races throughout the world with the development of high potential racing machines. Its racing activities are an important source for the creation of leading edge technologies used in the development of Honda motorcycles. HRC also contributes to the advancement of motorcycle sports through a range of activities that include sales of production racing motorcycles, support for satellite teams, and rider education programs.</p>
<p>Soichiro Honda, being a race driver himself, could not stay out of international <a href="/wiki/Motorsport" title="Motorsport">motorsport</a>. In 1959, Honda entered five motorcycles into the <a href="/wiki/Isle_of_Man_TT" title="Isle of Man TT">Isle of Man TT</a> race, the most prestigious motorcycle race in the world. While always having powerful engines, it took until 1961 for Honda to tune their chassis well enough to allow <a href="/wiki/Mike_Hailwood" title="Mike Hailwood">Mike Hailwood</a> to claim their first <a href="/wiki/Grand_Prix_motorcycle_racing" title="Grand Prix motorcycle racing">Grand Prix</a> victories in the 125 and 250&#160;<a href="/wiki/Cubic_centimetre" title="Cubic centimetre">cc</a> classes. Hailwood would later pick up their first Senior TT wins in 1966 and <a href="/wiki/1967_Isle_of_Man_TT" title="1967 Isle of Man TT">1967</a>. Honda's race bikes were known for their "sleek &amp; stylish design" and exotic engine configurations, such as the 5-cylinder, 22,000&#160;rpm, 125&#160;cc bike and their 6-cylinder 250&#160;cc and 297&#160;cc bikes.</p>
<p>In 1979, Honda returned to <a href="/wiki/Grand_Prix_motorcycle_racing" title="Grand Prix motorcycle racing">Grand Prix motorcycle racing</a> with the <a href="/wiki/Monocoque" title="Monocoque">monocoque</a>-framed, <a href="/wiki/Four-stroke_engine" title="Four-stroke engine">four-stroke</a> <a href="/wiki/Honda_NR500" title="Honda NR500">NR500</a>. The <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_Motocyclisme" title="Fédération Internationale de Motocyclisme">FIM</a> rules limited engines to four cylinders, so the NR500 had non-circular, 'race-track', cylinders, each with 8 valves and two connecting rods, in order to provide sufficient valve area to compete with the dominant <a href="/wiki/Two-stroke_engine" title="Two-stroke engine">two-stroke</a> racers. Unfortunately, it seemed Honda tried to accomplish too much at one time and the experiment failed. For the 1982 season, Honda debuted their first two-stroke race bike, the NS500 and in <a href="/wiki/1983_Grand_Prix_motorcycle_racing_season" title="1983 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season">1983</a>, Honda won their first 500&#160;cc <a href="/wiki/Grand_Prix_motorcycle_racing" title="Grand Prix motorcycle racing">Grand Prix</a> World Championship with <a href="/wiki/Freddie_Spencer" title="Freddie Spencer">Freddie Spencer</a>. Since then, Honda has become a dominant marque in motorcycle Grand Prix racing, winning a plethora of top level titles with riders such as <a href="/wiki/Mick_Doohan" title="Mick Doohan">Mick Doohan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Valentino_Rossi" title="Valentino Rossi">Valentino Rossi</a>. Honda also head the number of wins at the <a href="/wiki/Isle_of_Man_TT" title="Isle of Man TT">Isle of Man TT</a> having notched up 227 victories in the solo classes and <a href="/wiki/Sidecar_TT" title="Sidecar TT">Sidecar TT</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> including <a href="/wiki/Ian_Hutchinson_(motorcycle_racer)" title="Ian Hutchinson (motorcycle racer)">Ian Hutchinson</a>'s clean sweep at the <a href="/wiki/2010_Isle_of_Man_TT" title="2010 Isle of Man TT">2010 races</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup> The outright lap record on the <a href="/wiki/Snaefell_Mountain_Course" title="Snaefell Mountain Course">Snaefell Mountain Course</a> is also held by Honda, set at the 2015 TT by <a href="/wiki/John_McGuinness_(motorcycle_racer)" title="John McGuinness (motorcycle racer)">John McGuinness</a> at an average speed of 132.701&#160;mph (213.562&#160;km/h) on a <a href="/wiki/Honda_CBR1000RR" title="Honda CBR1000RR">Honda CBR1000RR</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the <a href="/wiki/Motocross_World_Championship" title="Motocross World Championship">Motocross World Championship</a>, Honda has claimed six world championships. In the <a href="/wiki/World_Enduro_Championship" title="World Enduro Championship">World Enduro Championship</a>, Honda has captured eight titles, most recently with <a href="/wiki/Stefan_Merriman" title="Stefan Merriman">Stefan Merriman</a> in 2003 and with <a href="/wiki/Mika_Ahola" title="Mika Ahola">Mika Ahola</a> from 2007 to 2010. In <a href="/wiki/Motorcycle_trials" title="Motorcycle trials">motorcycle trials</a>, Honda has claimed three world championships with Belgian rider <a href="/wiki/Eddy_Lejeune" title="Eddy Lejeune">Eddy Lejeune</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Electric_and_alternative_fuel_vehicles">Electric and alternative fuel vehicles</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg/220px-2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg" width="220" height="122" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg/330px-2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg/440px-2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2958" data-file-height="1638" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:2009_Honda_Civic_NGV--DC.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2009 <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_GX" title="Honda Civic GX">Honda Civic GX</a> hooked up to Phill refueling system</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Compressed_natural_gas">Compressed natural gas</span></h3>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_GX" title="Honda Civic GX">Honda Civic GX</a> was for a long time the only purpose-built <a href="/wiki/Natural_gas_vehicle" title="Natural gas vehicle">natural gas vehicle</a> (NGV) commercially available in some parts of the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup> The Honda Civic GX first appeared in 1998 as a factory-modified Civic LX that had been designed to run exclusively on <a href="/wiki/Compressed_natural_gas" title="Compressed natural gas">compressed natural gas</a>. The car looks and drives just like a contemporary <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic" title="Honda Civic">Honda Civic</a> LX, but does not run on gasoline. In 2001, the Civic GX was rated the cleanest-burning internal combustion engine in the world by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency" title="United States Environmental Protection Agency">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA).<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup></p>
<p>First leased to the City of Los Angeles, in 2005, Honda started offering the GX directly to the public through factory trained dealers certified to service the GX. Before that, only <a href="/wiki/Fleet_vehicles" class="mw-redirect" title="Fleet vehicles">fleets</a> were eligible to purchase a new Civic GX. In 2006, the Civic GX was released in New York, making it the second state where the consumer is able to buy the car.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup></p>
<p>In June 2015, Honda announced its decision to phase out the commercialization of natural-gas powered vehicles to focus on the development of a new generation of <a href="/wiki/Electric_vehicle" title="Electric vehicle">electrified vehicles</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">hybrids</a>, <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_electric_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Plug-in electric car">plug-in electric cars</a> and hydrogen-powered <a href="/wiki/Fuel_cell_vehicle" title="Fuel cell vehicle">fuel cell vehicles</a>. Since 2008, Honda has sold about 16,000 natural-gas vehicles, mainly to taxi and commercial fleets.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg/220px-Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg" width="220" height="318" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg/330px-Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg/440px-Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg 2x" data-file-width="986" data-file-height="1423" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_Civic_Clean_Models_USA_%26_BRA.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Top: Brazilian <a href="/wiki/Flexible-fuel_vehicle" title="Flexible-fuel vehicle">flexible-fuel</a> <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic" title="Honda Civic">Honda Civic</a>. Below: U.S. <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_Hybrid" title="Honda Civic Hybrid">Honda Civic Hybrid</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Flexible-fuel">Flexible-fuel</span></h3>
<p>Honda's Brazilian subsidiary launched <a href="/wiki/Flexible-fuel_vehicle" title="Flexible-fuel vehicle">flexible-fuel</a> versions for the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic" title="Honda Civic">Honda Civic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit" title="Honda Fit">Honda Fit</a> in late 2006. As other Brazilian flex-fuel vehicles, these models run on any blend of <a href="/wiki/Hydrous" class="mw-redirect" title="Hydrous">hydrous</a> ethanol (<a href="/wiki/Neat_alcohol_fuel" class="mw-redirect" title="Neat alcohol fuel">E100</a>) and <a href="/wiki/E20_fuel" class="mw-redirect" title="E20 fuel">E20-E25 gasoline</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-HondaFlex_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HondaFlex-66">[66]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4Rodas_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4Rodas-67">[67]</a></sup> Initially, and in order to test the market preferences, the carmaker decided to produce a limited share of the vehicles with flex-fuel engines, 33 percent of the Civic production and 28 percent of the Fit models.<sup id="cite_ref-HondaFlex_66-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HondaFlex-66">[66]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4Rodas_67-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4Rodas-67">[67]</a></sup> Also, the sale price for the flex-fuel version was higher than the respective gasoline versions, around US$1,000 premium for the Civic, and US$650 for the Fit, despite the fact that all other flex-fuel vehicles sold in Brazil had the same tag price as their gasoline versions.<sup id="cite_ref-4Rodas_67-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4Rodas-67">[67]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup> In July 2009, Honda launched in the Brazilian market its third flexible-fuel car, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_City" title="Honda City">Honda City</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup></p>
<p>During the last two months of 2006, both flex-fuel models sold 2,427 cars against 8,546 gasoline-powered automobiles,<sup id="cite_ref-ANFAVEA06_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ANFAVEA06-71">[71]</a></sup> jumping to 41,990 flex-fuel cars in 2007,<sup id="cite_ref-ANFAVEA07_72-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ANFAVEA07-72">[72]</a></sup> and reaching 93,361 in 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-ANFAVEA08_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ANFAVEA08-73">[73]</a></sup> Due to the success of the flex versions, by early 2009 a hundred percent of Honda's automobile production for the Brazilian market is now flexible-fuel, and only a small percentage of gasoline version is produced in Brazil for exports.<sup id="cite_ref-ANFAVEA09_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ANFAVEA09-74">[74]</a></sup></p>
<p>In March 2009, Honda launched in the Brazilian market the first flex-fuel motorcycle in the world. Produced by its Brazilian subsidiary Moto Honda da Amazônia, the <a href="/w/index.php?title=CG_150_Titan_Mix&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="CG 150 Titan Mix (page does not exist)">CG 150 Titan Mix</a> is sold for around US$2,700.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Hybrid_electric">Hybrid electric</span></h3>
<p>In late 1999, Honda launched the first commercial <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Hybrid electric car">hybrid electric car</a> sold in the U.S. market, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Insight" title="Honda Insight">Honda Insight</a>, just one month before the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Prius" title="Toyota Prius">Toyota Prius</a>, and initially sold for US$20,000.<sup id="cite_ref-TwoBillion_78-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TwoBillion-78">[78]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NYT2_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT2-79">[79]</a></sup> The first-generation Insight was produced from 2000 to 2006 and had a <a href="/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles" title="Fuel economy in automobiles">fuel economy</a> of 70 miles per US gallon (3.4&#160;L/100&#160;km; 84&#160;mpg<sub>‑imp</sub>) for the EPA's highway rating, the most fuel-efficient mass-produced car at the time.<sup id="cite_ref-TwoBillion_78-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TwoBillion-78">[78]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NYT2_79-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT2-79">[79]</a></sup> Total global sales for the Insight amounted to only around 18,000 vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT2_79-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT2-79">[79]</a></sup> Cumulative global sales reached 100,000 hybrids in 2005 and 200,000 in 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda1mi_80-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda1mi-80">[80]</a></sup></p>
<p>Honda introduced the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Insight#Second_generation_.282009.E2.80.932014.29" title="Honda Insight">second-generation Insight</a> in Japan in February 2009, and released it in other markets through 2009 and in the U.S. market in April 2009. At $19,800 as a five-door hatchback it will be the least expensive hybrid available in the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg/220px-2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg" width="220" height="127" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg/330px-2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg/440px-2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2376" data-file-height="1367" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:2010_Honda_Insight--DC.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2010 <a href="/wiki/Honda_Insight" title="Honda Insight">Honda Insight</a> <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">hybrid electric vehicle</a> (Second generation)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Since 2002, Honda has also been selling the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic_Hybrid" title="Honda Civic Hybrid">Honda Civic Hybrid</a> (2003 model) in the U.S. market.<sup id="cite_ref-TwoBillion_78-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TwoBillion-78">[78]</a></sup> It was followed by the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord_Hybrid" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Accord Hybrid">Honda Accord Hybrid</a>, offered in model years 2005 through 2007. Sales of the <a href="/wiki/Honda_CR-Z" title="Honda CR-Z">Honda CR-Z</a> began in Japan in February 2010, becoming Honda's third hybrid electric car in the market.<sup id="cite_ref-GCC0210_82-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GCC0210-82">[82]</a></sup> As of February 2011<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Honda&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, Honda was producing around 200,000 hybrids a year in Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup></p>
<p>Sales of the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit_Hybrid" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Fit Hybrid">Fit Hybrid</a> began in Japan in October 2010, at the time, the lowest price for a gasoline-hybrid electric vehicle sold in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-JapHEV_84-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-JapHEV-84">[84]</a></sup> The European version, called <a href="/wiki/Honda_Jazz_Hybrid" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Jazz Hybrid">Honda Jazz Hybrid</a>, was released in early 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT0810_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT0810-85">[85]</a></sup> During 2011 Honda launched three hybrid models available only in Japan, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit#Fit_Shuttle_and_Fit_Shuttle_hybrid_.282011.29" title="Honda Fit">Fit Shuttle Hybrid</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honda_Freed_Hybrid" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Freed Hybrid">Freed Hybrid</a> and Freed Spike Hybrid.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda1mi_80-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda1mi-80">[80]</a></sup></p>
<p>Honda's cumulative global hybrid sales passed the 1 million unit milestone at the end of September 2012, 12 years and 11 months after sales of the first generation Insight began in Japan November 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda1mi_80-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda1mi-80">[80]</a></sup> A total of 187,851 hybrids were sold worldwide in 2013, and 158,696 hybrids during the first six months of 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda2013_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda2013-86">[86]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Honda062014_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda062014-87">[87]</a></sup> As of June 2014<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Honda&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, Honda has sold more than 1.35&#160;million hybrids worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda1mi_80-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda1mi-80">[80]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Honda2013_86-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda2013-86">[86]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Honda062014_87-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda062014-87">[87]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Hydrogen_fuel_cell">Hydrogen fuel cell</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:FCX_Clarity.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/FCX_Clarity.jpg/220px-FCX_Clarity.jpg" width="220" height="112" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/FCX_Clarity.jpg/330px-FCX_Clarity.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/FCX_Clarity.jpg/440px-FCX_Clarity.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3209" data-file-height="1631" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:FCX_Clarity.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Honda_FCX_Clarity" title="Honda FCX Clarity">Honda FCX Clarity</a> <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen" title="Hydrogen">hydrogen</a> <a href="/wiki/Fuel_cell" title="Fuel cell">fuel cell</a> vehicle</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Takanezawa" class="mw-redirect" title="Takanezawa">Takanezawa</a>, Japan, on 16 June 2008, Honda Motors produced the first assembly-line <a href="/wiki/Honda_FCX_Clarity" title="Honda FCX Clarity">FCX Clarity</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_vehicle" title="Hybrid vehicle">hybrid</a> <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen_vehicle" title="Hydrogen vehicle">hydrogen</a> <a href="/wiki/Fuel_cell_vehicle" title="Fuel cell vehicle">fuel cell vehicle</a>. More efficient than a <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">gas-electric hybrid vehicle</a>, the FCX Clarity combines <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen" title="Hydrogen">hydrogen</a> and <a href="/wiki/Oxygen" title="Oxygen">oxygen</a> from ordinary air to generate electricity for an electric motor. In July 2014 Honda announced the end of production of the <a href="/wiki/Honda_FCX_Clarity" title="Honda FCX Clarity">Honda FCX Clarity</a> for the 2015 model.<sup id="cite_ref-ProdEnd_88-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ProdEnd-88">[88]</a></sup></p>
<p>The vehicle itself does not emit any <a href="/wiki/Pollutants" class="mw-redirect" title="Pollutants">pollutants</a> and its only by products are heat and water. The FCX Clarity also has an advantage over gas-electric hybrids in that it does not use an <a href="/wiki/Internal_combustion_engine" title="Internal combustion engine">internal combustion engine</a> to propel itself. Like a gas-electric hybrid, it uses a <a href="/wiki/Lithium_ion_battery" class="mw-redirect" title="Lithium ion battery">lithium ion battery</a> to assist the fuel cell during acceleration and capture energy through <a href="/wiki/Regenerative_braking" class="mw-redirect" title="Regenerative braking">regenerative braking</a>, thus improving fuel efficiency. The lack of hydrogen filling stations throughout developed countries will keep production volumes low.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup> Honda will release the vehicle in groups of 150. California is the only U.S. market with infrastructure for fueling such a vehicle, though the number of stations is still limited. Building more stations is expensive, as the <a href="/wiki/California_Air_Resources_Board" title="California Air Resources Board">California Air Resources Board</a> (CARB) granted $6.8&#160;million for four H2 fueling stations, costing $1.7&#160;million USD each.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup></p>
<p>Honda views hydrogen fuel cell vehicles as the long term replacement of piston cars, not battery cars.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">[92]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Plug-in_electric_vehicles">Plug-in electric vehicles</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg/220px-Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg/330px-Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg/440px-Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4032" data-file-height="3024" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_Fit_EV_2010_LA_Auto_Show.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit_EV" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Fit EV">Honda Fit EV</a> <a href="/wiki/Concept_car" title="Concept car">concept</a> unveiled at the 2010 <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Auto_Show" class="mw-redirect" title="Los Angeles Auto Show">Los Angeles Auto Show</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Battery_electric_vehicle" title="Battery electric vehicle">all-electric</a> <a href="/wiki/Honda_EV_Plus" title="Honda EV Plus">Honda EV Plus</a> was introduced in 1997 as a result of <a href="/wiki/California_Air_Resources_Board" title="California Air Resources Board">CARB</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Zero-emissions_vehicle" title="Zero-emissions vehicle">zero-emissions vehicle</a> mandate and was available only for leasing in California. The EV plus was the first <a href="/wiki/Battery_electric_vehicle" title="Battery electric vehicle">battery electric vehicle</a> from a major automaker with non-<a href="/wiki/Lead%E2%80%93acid_battery" title="Lead–acid battery">lead–acid batteries</a> The EV Plus had an <a href="/wiki/All-electric_range" title="All-electric range">all-electric range</a> of 100&#160;mi (160&#160;km). Around 276 units were sold in the U.S. and production ended in 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-Rand02_93-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rand02-93">[93]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Boschert06_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Boschert06-94">[94]</a></sup></p>
<p>The all-electric <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit_EV" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Fit EV">Honda Fit EV</a> was introduced in 2012 and has a range of 82&#160;mi (132&#160;km).<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">[95]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/All-electric_car" class="mw-redirect" title="All-electric car">all-electric car</a> was launched in the U.S. to retail customers in July 2012 with initial availability limited to California and Oregon.<sup id="cite_ref-FitEV0712_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FitEV0712-96">[96]</a></sup> Production is limited to only 1,100 units over the first three years. A total of 1,007 units have been leased in the U.S. through September 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-PEVUSales2012_97-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PEVUSales2012-97">[97]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-PEVUSales2013_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PEVUSales2013-98">[98]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-USPEVsales092014_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USPEVsales092014-99">[99]</a></sup> The Fit EV was released in Japan through leasing to local government and corporate customers in August 2012. Availability in the Japanese market is limited to 200 units during its first two years.<sup id="cite_ref-FitJap_100-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FitJap-100">[100]</a></sup> In July 2014 Honda announced the end of production of the Fit EV for the 2015 model.<sup id="cite_ref-ProdEnd_88-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ProdEnd-88">[88]</a></sup></p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord_Plug-in_Hybrid" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Accord Plug-in Hybrid">Honda Accord Plug-in Hybrid</a> was introduced in 2013 and has an <a href="/wiki/All-electric_range" title="All-electric range">all-electric range</a> of 13&#160;mi (21&#160;km)<sup id="cite_ref-2014Accord_101-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2014Accord-101">[101]</a></sup> Sales began in the U.S. in January 2013 and the <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_hybrid" title="Plug-in hybrid">plug-in hybrid</a> is available only in California and New York.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">[102]</a></sup> A total of 835 units have been sold in the U.S. through September 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-PEVUSales2012_97-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PEVUSales2012-97">[97]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-PEVUSales2013_98-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PEVUSales2013-98">[98]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-USPEVsales092014_99-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USPEVsales092014-99">[99]</a></sup> The Accord PHEV was introduced in Japan in June 2013 and is available only for leasing, primarily to corporations and government agencies.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">[103]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing">Marketing</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Japan">Japan</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg/220px-Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg" width="220" height="130" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg/330px-Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg/440px-Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1000" data-file-height="591" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_CLIO_Japan_Car_dealership_Saitama.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Honda Clio (<a href="/wiki/Saitama,_Saitama" title="Saitama, Saitama">Saitama</a>, Japan)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Starting in 1978, Honda in Japan decided to diversify its sales distribution channels, and created <b>Honda Verno</b>, which sold established products with a higher content of standard equipment and a more sporting nature.<sup id="cite_ref-n5_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-n5-104">[104]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">[105]</a></sup> The establishment of <i>Honda Verno</i> coincided with its new sports compact, called the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Prelude" title="Honda Prelude">Honda Prelude</a>. Later, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Vigor" title="Honda Vigor">Honda Vigor</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Ballade" title="Honda Ballade">Honda Ballade</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Quint" title="Honda Quint">Honda Quint</a> were added to <i>Honda Verno</i> stores. This approach was implemented due to efforts in place by rival Japanese automakers <a href="/wiki/Toyota#Japan" title="Toyota">Toyota</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nissan#Japan" title="Nissan">Nissan</a>.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg/220px-Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg" width="220" height="162" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg/330px-Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg/440px-Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2510" data-file-height="1850" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Honda_Cars_Osaka_Nagahori.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Honda Primo (<a href="/wiki/Osaka" title="Osaka">Osaka</a>)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>As sales progressed, Honda created two more sales channels, called <b>Honda Clio</b> in 1984, and <b>Honda Primo</b> in 1985. The <i>Honda Clio</i> chain sold products that were traditionally associated with Honda dealerships before 1978, like the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord" title="Honda Accord">Honda Accord</a>, and <i>Honda Primo</i> sold the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Civic" title="Honda Civic">Honda Civic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kei_car" title="Kei car">kei cars</a>, such as the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Today" title="Honda Today">Honda Today</a>, <a href="/wiki/Supermini" title="Supermini">superminis</a> like the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Capa" title="Honda Capa">Honda Capa</a>, along with other Honda products, such as farm equipment, lawn mowers, portable generators, marine equipment, plus motorcycles and scooters like the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Super_Cub" title="Honda Super Cub">Honda Super Cub</a>. A styling tradition was established when <i>Honda Primo</i> and <i>Clio</i> began operations, in that all <i>Verno</i> products had the rear license plate installed in the rear bumper, while <i>Primo</i> and <i>Clio</i> products had the rear license plate installed on the trunk lid or rear door for minivans.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg/220px-HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg/330px-HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg/440px-HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="960" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:HondaVerno_2nddealership.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Honda Verno (2008)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>As time progressed and sales began to diminish partly due to the collapse of the Japanese "<a href="/wiki/Japan_%22bubble_economy%22" class="mw-redirect" title="Japan &quot;bubble economy&quot;">bubble economy</a>", "supermini" and "kei" vehicles that were specific to <i>Honda Primo</i> were "<a href="/wiki/Badge_engineered" class="mw-redirect" title="Badge engineered">badge engineered</a>" and sold at the other two sales channels, thereby providing smaller vehicles that sold better at both <i>Honda Verno</i> and <i>Honda Clio</i> locations. As of March 2006, the three sales chains were discontinued, with the establishment of <i>Honda Cars</i> dealerships.<sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup> While the network was disbanded, some Japanese Honda dealerships still use the network names, offering all Japanese market Honda cars at all locations.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg/220px-HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg/330px-HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg/440px-HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2560" data-file-height="1920" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:HONDA_Bike_Shop.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Honda Wing motorcycle dealership (Japan)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Honda sells genuine accessories through a separate retail chain called <i><a href="https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%83%9B%E3%83%B3%E3%83%80%E3%82%A2%E3%82%AF%E3%82%BB%E3%82%B9" class="extiw" title="ja:ホンダアクセス">Honda Access</a></i> for both their motorcycle, scooter and automobile products. In cooperation with corporate "<a href="/wiki/Keiretsu" title="Keiretsu">keiretsu</a>" partner <a href="/wiki/Pioneer_Corporation" title="Pioneer Corporation">Pioneer</a>, Honda sells an aftermarket line of audio and <a href="/wiki/Internavi" title="Internavi">in-car navigation</a> equipment that can be installed in any vehicle under the brand name <a href="https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%82%AE%E3%83%A3%E3%82%B6%E3%82%BA" class="extiw" title="ja:ギャザズ">Gathers</a>, which is available at Honda Access locations as well as Japanese auto parts retailers, such as <a href="/wiki/Autobacs" class="mw-redirect" title="Autobacs">Autobacs</a>. Buyers of used vehicles are directed to a specific Honda retail chain that sells only used vehicles called <i><a href="https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auto_Terrace" class="extiw" title="ja:Auto Terrace">Honda Auto Terrace</a>.</i></p>
<p>In the spring of 2012, Honda in Japan introduced <i><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.honda.co.jp/hondacars/smallstore/?from=HondaCars-footer">Honda Cars Small Store</a></i> (Japanese) which is devoted to compact cars like the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Fit" title="Honda Fit">Honda Fit</a>, and <i><a href="/wiki/Kei_car" title="Kei car">kei</a></i> vehicles like the <a href="/wiki/Honda_N-One" title="Honda N-One">Honda N-One</a> and <a href="/wiki/Honda_S660" title="Honda S660">Honda S660</a> roadster.</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="International_efforts">International efforts</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:RichmondHillHonda.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/RichmondHillHonda.jpg/220px-RichmondHillHonda.jpg" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/RichmondHillHonda.jpg/330px-RichmondHillHonda.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/RichmondHillHonda.jpg/440px-RichmondHillHonda.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4928" data-file-height="3264" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:RichmondHillHonda.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A Honda dealership in Ontario, Canada</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 2003, Honda released its <i><a href="/wiki/Cog_(television_commercial)" class="mw-redirect" title="Cog (television commercial)">Cog</a></i> advertisement in the UK and on the Internet. To make the ad, the engineers at Honda constructed a <a href="/wiki/Rube_Goldberg_Machine" class="mw-redirect" title="Rube Goldberg Machine">Rube Goldberg Machine</a> made entirely out of car parts from a <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord_(Japan_and_Europe_seventh_generation)" title="Honda Accord (Japan and Europe seventh generation)">Honda Accord Touring</a>. To the chagrin of the engineers at Honda, all the parts were taken from two of only six hand-assembled <a href="/wiki/Pre-production_car" title="Pre-production car">pre-production</a> models of the Accord. The advertisement depicted a single cog which sets off a chain of events that ends with the Honda Accord moving and <a href="/wiki/Garrison_Keillor" title="Garrison Keillor">Garrison Keillor</a> speaking the tagline, "Isn't it nice when things just... work?" It took 606 takes to get it perfect.<sup id="cite_ref-Honda_2003_UK_Ad_campaign_107-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Honda_2003_UK_Ad_campaign-107">[107]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2004, they produced the <i><a href="/wiki/Grrr_(advertisement)" title="Grrr (advertisement)">Grrr</a></i> advert, usually immediately followed by a shortened version of the 2005 <i>Impossible Dream</i> advert.</p>
<p>In December 2005, Honda released <i><a href="/wiki/Impossible_Dream_(Honda_advert)" class="mw-redirect" title="Impossible Dream (Honda advert)">The Impossible Dream</a></i> a two-minute panoramic advertisement filmed in New Zealand, Japan and Argentina which illustrates the founder's dream to build performance vehicles. While singing the song "<a href="/wiki/The_Impossible_Dream_(The_Quest)" title="The Impossible Dream (The Quest)">Impossible Dream</a>", a man reaches for his racing helmet, leaves his trailer on a minibike, then rides a succession of vintage Honda vehicles: a motorcycle, then a car, then a powerboat, then goes over a waterfall only to reappear piloting a <a href="/wiki/Hot_air_balloon" title="Hot air balloon">hot air balloon</a>, with Garrison Keillor saying "I couldn't have put it better myself" as the song ends. The song is from the 1960s musical <i><a href="/wiki/Man_Of_La_Mancha" class="mw-redirect" title="Man Of La Mancha">Man Of La Mancha</a></i>, sung by <a href="/wiki/Andy_Williams" title="Andy Williams">Andy Williams</a>.</p>
<p>In 2006, Honda released its <i>Choir</i> advertisement, for the UK and the internet. This had a 60-person choir who sang the car noises as film of the Honda Civic are shown.</p>
<p>In the mid to late 2000s in the United States, during model close-out sales for the current year before the start of the new <a href="/wiki/Model_year" title="Model year">model year</a>, Honda's advertising has had an <a href="/wiki/Animated_character" class="mw-redirect" title="Animated character">animated character</a> known simply as <a href="/wiki/Mr._Opportunity" title="Mr. Opportunity">Mr. Opportunity</a>, voiced by <a href="/wiki/Rob_Paulsen" title="Rob Paulsen">Rob Paulsen</a>. The casual looking man talked about various deals offered by Honda and ended with the phrase "I'm Mr. Opportunity, and I'm knockin'", followed by him "knocking" on the television screen or "thumping" the speaker at the end of radio ads. In addition, commercials for Honda's international hatchback, the Jazz, are parodies of well-known pop culture images such as <a href="/wiki/Tetris" title="Tetris">Tetris</a> and <a href="/wiki/Thomas_The_Tank_Engine" class="mw-redirect" title="Thomas The Tank Engine">Thomas The Tank Engine</a>.</p>
<p>In late 2006, Honda released an ad with <a href="/wiki/ASIMO" title="ASIMO">ASIMO</a> exploring a museum, looking at the exhibits with almost childlike wonderment (spreading out its arms in the aerospace exhibit, waving hello to an <a href="/wiki/Astronaut" title="Astronaut">astronaut</a> suit that resembles him, etc.), while Garrison Keillor ruminates on progress. It concludes with the tagline: "More forwards please".</p>
<p>Honda also sponsored <a href="/wiki/ITV_Sport" title="ITV Sport">ITV's</a> coverage of <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> in the UK for 2007. However they had announced that they would not continue in 2008 due to the sponsorship price requested by ITV being too high.</p>
<p>In May 2007, focuses on their strengths in racing and the use of the Red H badge – a symbol of what is termed as "Hondamentalism". The campaign highlights the lengths that Honda engineers go to in order to get the most out of an engine, whether it is for bikes, cars, powerboats – even lawnmowers. Honda released its <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.honda.co.uk/hondamentalism/?campaignid=CM059600W01G">Hondamentalism</a> campaign. In the TV spot, Garrison Keillor says, "An engineer once said to build something great is like swimming in honey", while Honda engineers in white suits walk and run towards a great light, battling strong winds and flying debris, holding on to anything that will keep them from being blown away. Finally one of the engineers walks towards a red light, his hand outstretched. A web address is shown for the Hondamentalism website. The digital campaign aims to show how visitors to the site share many of the Hondamentalist characteristics.</p>
<p>At the beginning of 2008, Honda released – the <i>Problem Playground</i>. The advert outlines Honda's environmental responsibility, demonstrating a hybrid engine, more efficient solar panels and the <a href="/wiki/FCX_Clarity" class="mw-redirect" title="FCX Clarity">FCX Clarity</a>, a hydrogen powered car. The 90 second advert has large scale puzzles, involving <a href="/wiki/Rubik%27s_Cube" title="Rubik's Cube">Rubik's Cubes</a>, large shapes and a 3-dimensional puzzle.</p>
<p>On 29 May 2008, Honda, in partnership with <a href="/wiki/Channel_4" title="Channel 4">Channel 4</a>, broadcast a live advertisement. It showed <a href="/wiki/Skydivers" class="mw-redirect" title="Skydivers">skydivers</a> jumping from an aeroplane over Spain and forming the letters H, O, N, D and A in mid-air. This live advertisement is generally agreed to be the first of its kind on British television. The advert lasted three minutes.<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108">[108]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2009, American Honda released the <i>Dream the Impossible</i> documentary series, a collection of 5–8 minute web vignettes that focus on the core philosophies of Honda. Current short films include <i>Failure: The Secret to Success</i>, <i>Kick Out the Ladder</i> and <i>Mobility 2088</i>. They have Honda employees as well as <a href="/wiki/Danica_Patrick" title="Danica Patrick">Danica Patrick</a>, <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Guest" title="Christopher Guest">Christopher Guest</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ben_Bova" title="Ben Bova">Ben Bova</a>, Chee Pearlman, <a href="/wiki/Joe_Johnston" title="Joe Johnston">Joe Johnston</a> and <a href="/wiki/Orson_Scott_Card" title="Orson Scott Card">Orson Scott Card</a>. The film series plays at dreams.honda.com.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sports">Sports</span></h3>
<p>In Australia, Honda advertised heavily during most motor racing telecasts, and was the official sponsor of the 2006 FIA Formula 1 telecast on broadcaster channel "Ten". In fact, it was the only manufacturer involved in the 2006 <a href="/wiki/Indy_Racing_League" class="mw-redirect" title="Indy Racing League">Indy Racing League</a> season. In a series of adverts promoting the history of Honda's racing heritage, Honda claimed it "built" cars that won 72 Formula 1 Grand Prix. Skeptics<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_attributions" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span title="The material near this tag possibly uses too-vague attribution or weasel words. (July 2009)">who?</span></a></i>]</sup> have accused Honda of interpreting its racing history rather liberally, saying that virtually all of the 72 victories were achieved by Honda <i>powered</i> (engined) machines, whereas the cars themselves were designed and built by Lotus F1, Williams F1, and McLaren F1 teams, respectively. However, former and current staff of the McLaren F1 team have reiterated that Honda contributed more than just engines and provided various chassis, tooling, and aerodynamic parts as well as funding.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="reliable source needed for the whole sentence (August 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>The late F1 driver <a href="/wiki/Ayrton_Senna" title="Ayrton Senna">Ayrton Senna</a> stated that Honda probably played the most significant role in his three world championships. He had immense respect for founder, Soichiro Honda, and had a good relationship with Nobuhiko Kawamoto, the chairman of Honda at that time. Senna once called Honda "the greatest company in the world".<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="reliable source needed for the whole sentence (August 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>As part of its marketing campaign, Honda is an official partner and sponsor of the <a href="/wiki/National_Hockey_League" title="National Hockey League">National Hockey League</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Anaheim_Ducks" title="Anaheim Ducks">Anaheim Ducks</a> of the NHL, and the arena named after it: <a href="/wiki/Honda_Center" title="Honda Center">Honda Center</a>. Honda also sponsors <a href="/wiki/The_Honda_Classic" title="The Honda Classic">The Honda Classic</a> golf tournament and is a sponsor of <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Soccer" title="Major League Soccer">Major League Soccer</a>. The "<a href="/wiki/Honda_Player_of_the_Year" class="mw-redirect" title="Honda Player of the Year">Honda Player of the Year</a>" award is presented in United States soccer. The "<a href="/wiki/Honda_Sports_Award" title="Honda Sports Award">Honda Sports Award</a>" is given to the best female athlete in each of twelve college sports in the United States. One of the twelve Honda Sports Award winners is chosen to receive the <a href="/wiki/Honda-Broderick_Cup" title="Honda-Broderick Cup">Honda-Broderick Cup</a>, as "Collegiate Woman Athlete of the Year."</p>
<p>Honda will be sponsoring <a href="/wiki/La_Liga" title="La Liga">La Liga</a> club <a href="/wiki/Valencia_CF" title="Valencia CF">Valencia CF</a> starting from <a href="/wiki/2014%E2%80%9315_La_Liga" title="2014–15 La Liga">2014–15 season</a>. <a href="/wiki/Valencia_CF" title="Valencia CF">Valencia CF</a> will carry <i>Honda Cars Valencia</i> insignia on their football kits.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>Honda has been a presenting sponsor of the <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Marathon" title="Los Angeles Marathon">Los Angeles Marathon</a> since 2010 in a three-year sponsorship deal, with winners of the LA Marathon receiving a free <a href="/wiki/Honda_Accord" title="Honda Accord">Honda Accord</a>. Since 1989, the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Campus_All-Star_Challenge" title="Honda Campus All-Star Challenge">Honda Campus All-Star Challenge</a> has been a <a href="/wiki/Quizbowl" class="mw-redirect" title="Quizbowl">quizbowl</a> tournament for <a href="/wiki/Historically_black_colleges_and_universities" title="Historically black colleges and universities">Historically black colleges and universities</a>.</p>
